Recall that the Maclaurin series of $\ln(1+x)$ is

\begin{align*}\ln(1+x) = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n-1}}{n}x^n\end{align*}

with radius of convergence \emph{R=1}.

If we put \emph{x=1/2}, then we obtain the given series and hence we
find

\begin{align*}\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{n-1}}{n 2^n} = \ln(1+1/2)= \ln(3/2)\end{align*}
